<p><span class="os-raise-ib-tooltip" data-schema-version="1.0" data-store="glossary-tooltip">Horizontal dilations</span> that stretch and compress <em>linear</em> functions are difficult to identify from graphs because they can appear as if they are vertical dilations. However, they are different because: </p>
<ul>
<li>The changes to the function are applied to the input values of a function when the transformation is a <em>horizontal dilation</em>. </li>
<li>The changes to the function are applied to the output values of a function when the transformation is a <em>vertical dilation</em>.</li>
</ul>
